title: For Sale:  1927 Colt - Argentine Federal Goverment issued 1911-A1 45ACP
postcontent:
In 1927, the Argentina Arsenal "DGFM-FMAP" began manufacturing the Model 1911A1. The slide is marked with two lines and reads "EJERCITO ARGENTINO SIST.COLT.CAL. 11.25mm MOD.1927" which means Army of Argentina.  These guns were made in Argentina under license from Colt, with Colt machinery, and with help & supervision from Colt engineers, and are known as "Model 1927 Sistema Colt" or Colt system. 

This particular "Sistema Colt" has matching serial numbers on the frame, slide, barrel and every single part is original with the exception of the grips and the finish. I have added NEW very nice custom Cocobolo wood grips and will include a Wilson Combat magazine. Other than that, it is still in its original collector state! 

The gun is fully functional, however, has collector value since it has all matching serial numbered parts and is NOT an "import" which devalues the guns. This is a GENUINE Federal Government ISSUED Colt 1911-A1 made in Argentina by Colt machinery and Engineers. The military crest is clear and not rubbed off or worn down which also adds to its value.

This would make an AMAZING showpiece as well as a carry gun since it is fully functional 1911! I had this checked out & cleaned by a professional gunsmith specializing in 1911s. 

Not interested in trades at this time.

postcontent:
Made of 100% military-grade, 550 Paracord, contains approx 10 feet of usable cord if ever needed. These are 100% hand made by me when you place you order, all I need is the size of your wrist. 

1. Wrap a strip of plain paper around your wrist.  Don't make it tight, just comfortable. 

2. At the overlap, place a mark on the paper.

3. Measure from the end to the mark.

4. That is the measurement you should provide.  Please don't provide a measurement with a final increment of less than 1/8".

Ruger Model Security Six 357 Mag. The introduction of the Security Six and its variants marked Sturm Ruger’s first attempt to enter the double action revolver market. I have a S&W Model 59 9mm In Exe Condition, The 59 was S&W's first entry into hi Capacity Double Stacked Magazine Autos. They were originally offered in Blue or Nickel  finish with 2, 15rd Magazines. I have shot 30 rounds through this gun and it is very accurate, as they used a 1911 style Bushing System on the barrel insuring tight lockup. It looks as if the trigger pull is adjustable as well from a look at it field striped. 

I say this gun was manufactured in 1976 because there is a warranty card that Indicated the gun had a one year warranty from 1976...I  also have the original Wax Paper, Instruction manual etc...
This Gun was made to be used because the top of the gun has a satin finish vesus shiny nickel, so the shooter did not get blinded by the reflective nickel in sunlight. I would guess that less than 200 rounds have gone through this gun because it does not feel broken in yet. This gun is in Mint condition when you consider its age... I am trying to prep for the hollidays, in case you are wondering why I am selling

Collectors Place value on this gun between 450-900 dollars depending on condition and original box/paperwork.... From everything I have seen this should rank Higher on the Price scale.
